    <h1>Osteoporosis</h1></div><h2>Learn More About Osteoporosis</h2></div><div id="text-block-5" class="mk-text-block ">
<p>Osteoporosis is a disease of the skeletal system in which bone tissue and bone mass are deteriorating. When bones become porous, they weaken and are more prone to breaks and fractures. While it can develop at any age, osteoporosis is most common in women over the age of 50. Risk factors include a family history of the disease, being postmenopausal, a low calcium intake, sedentary lifestyle and smoking.</p>
<p>Vitamin D deficiency is also linked to osteoporosis, as this substance it essential for the formation and maintenance of bone tissue. The most common form of taking in Vitamin D is through both diet and exposure to the sun. People who spend more time indoors and who do not take supplements are at greater risk of Vitamin D deficiency, which can also lead to cardiovascular disease, skeletal deformities, cognitive impairments and asthma.</p>
</div>
